{"id":"1309.4894","submitter":"Hussein Aluie","authors":"Mike Rivera, Hussein Aluie, and Robert Ecke","title":"The direct enstrophy cascade of two-dimensional soap film flows","comments":"20 pages, 19 figures. Added a new Fig. 12, added a discussion on\n  ergodicity in relation to the Merilees & Warn predictions, and made minor\n  changes to the presentation","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1063/1.4873579","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.flu-dyn physics.geo-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We investigate the direct enstrophy cascade of two-dimensional decaying\nturbulence in a flowing soap film channel. We use a coarse-graining approach\nthat allows us to resolve the nonlinear dynamics and scale-coupling\nsimultaneously in space and in scale. From our data, we verify an exact\nrelation due to Eyink (1995) between traditional 3rd-order structure function\nand the enstrophy flux obtained by coarse-graining. We also present\nexperimental evidence that enstrophy cascades to smaller (larger) scales with a\n60% (40%) probability, in support of theoretical predictions by Merilees & Warn\n(1975) which appear to be valid in our flow owing to the ergodic nature of\nturbulence. We conjecture that their kinematic arguments break down in\nquasi-laminar 2D flows. We find some support for these ideas by using an\nEulerian coherent structure identification technique, which allows us to\ndetermine the effect of flow topology on the enstrophy cascade. A key finding\nis that \"centers\" are inefficient at transferring enstrophy between scales, in\ncontrast to \"saddle\" regions which transfer enstrophy to small scales with high\nefficiency.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 19 Sep 2013 08:57:00 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 10 Apr 2014 20:22:14 GMT"}],"update_date":"2015-06-17"}
